# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antlr-parser
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] In computer-based language recognition, **ANTLR** (pronounced *antler*), or **ANother Tool for Language Recognition**, is a parser generator that uses a LL(*) algorithm for parsing.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] ANTLR is the successor to the **Purdue Compiler Construction Tool Set** (**PCCTS**), first developed in 1989, and is under active development.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] Its maintainer is Professor Terence Parr of the University of San Francisco.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] ANTLR takes as input a grammar that specifies a language and generates as output source code for a recognizer of that language.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] While Version 3 supported generating code in the programming languages Ada95, ActionScript, C, C#, Java, JavaScript, Objective-C, Perl, Python, Ruby, and Standard ML, Version 4 at present targets C#, C++, Dart, Java, JavaScript, Go, PHP, Python (2 and 3), and Swift.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] A language is specified using a context-free grammar expressed using Extended Backus–Naur Form (EBNF).
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] ANTLR can generate lexers, parsers, tree parsers, and combined lexer-parsers.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] Parsers can automatically generate parse trees or abstract syntax trees, which can be further processed with tree parsers.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] ANTLR provides a single consistent notation for specifying lexers, parsers, and tree parsers.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] By default, ANTLR reads a grammar and generates a recognizer for the language defined by the grammar (i.e., a program that reads an input stream and generates an error if the input stream does not conform to the syntax specified by the grammar).
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] If there are no syntax errors, the default action is to simply exit without printing any message.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] In order to do something useful with the language, actions can be attached to grammar elements in the grammar.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] These actions are written in the programming language in which the recognizer is being generated.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] When the recognizer is being generated, the actions are embedded in the source code of the recognizer at the appropriate points.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] Actions can be used to build and check symbol tables and to emit instructions in a target language, in the case of a compiler.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] Other than lexers and parsers, ANTLR can be used to generate tree parsers.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] These are recognizers that process abstract syntax trees, which can be automatically generated by parsers.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] These tree parsers are unique to ANTLR and help processing abstract syntax trees.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] ANTLR 3 and ANTLR 4 are free software, published under a three-clause BSD License.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] Prior versions were released as public domain software.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] Documentation, derived from Parr's book *The Definitive ANTLR 4 Reference*, is included with the BSD-licensed ANTLR 4 source.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] Various plugins have been developed for the Eclipse development environment to support the ANTLR grammar, including ANTLR Studio, a proprietary product, as well as the "ANTLR 2" and "ANTLR 3" plugins for Eclipse hosted on SourceForge.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] ANTLR 4 deals with direct left recursion correctly, but not with left recursion in general, i.e., grammar rules *x* that refer to *y* that refer to *x*.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] As reported on the tools page of the ANTLR project, plug-ins that enable features like syntax highlighting, syntax error checking and code completion are freely available for the most common IDEs (Intellij IDEA, NetBeans, Eclipse, Visual Studio and Visual Studio Code).
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] Over 200 grammars implemented in ANTLR 4 are available on GitHub.
[src:antlr-parser/antlr] They range from grammars for a URL to grammars for entire languages like C, Java and Go.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] A **formal grammar** is a set of symbols and the production rules for rewriting some of them into every possible string of a formal language over an alphabet.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] A grammar does not describe the meaning of the strings—only their form.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] In applied mathematics, formal language theory is the discipline that studies formal grammars and languages.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Its applications are found in theoretical computer science, theoretical linguistics, formal semantics, mathematical logic, and other areas.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] A formal grammar is a set of rules for rewriting strings, along with a "start symbol" from which rewriting starts.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Therefore, a grammar is usually thought of as a language generator.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] However, it can also be used as the basis for a parser—a function in computing that determines whether a given string belongs to the language or is grammatically incorrect.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] To describe such parsers, formal language theory uses separate formalisms, known as automata theory.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] One result of automata theory is that it is not possible to design a recognizer for certain formal languages.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Many languages have the meanings of their strings structured according to their syntax—a practice known as compositional semantics.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] In these cases, the first step to describing the meaning of a string is to break it down part by part and look at its analyzed form (known as its parse tree in computer science, and as its deep structure in generative grammar).
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] A grammar mainly consists of a set of *production rules*, rewrite rules for transforming strings.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Each rule specifies a replacement of a particular string (its *left-hand side*) with another (its *right-hand side*).
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] A rule can be applied to each string that contains its left-hand side and produces a string in which an occurrence of that left-hand side has been replaced with its right-hand side.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Unlike a semi-Thue system, which is wholly defined by these rules, a grammar further distinguishes between two kinds of symbols: *nonterminal* and *terminal* symbols; each left-hand side must contain at least one nonterminal symbol.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] It also distinguishes a special nonterminal symbol, called the *start symbol*.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] The language generated by the grammar is defined to be the set of all strings without any nonterminal symbols that can be generated from the string consisting of a single start symbol by (possibly repeated) application of its rules in whatever way possible.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] If there are essentially different ways of generating the same single string, the grammar is said to be ambiguous.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] In the following examples, the terminal symbols are *a* and *b*, and the start symbol is *S*.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] then we start with *S*, and can choose a rule to apply to it.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] If we choose rule 1, we obtain the string *aSb*.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] If we then choose rule 1 again, we replace *S* with *aSb* and obtain the string *aaSbb*.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] If we now choose rule 2, we replace *S* with *ba* and obtain the string *aababb*, and are done.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] We can write this series of choices more briefly, using symbols: $S\Rightarrow aSb\Rightarrow aaSbb\Rightarrow aababb$ .
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] The language of the grammar is the infinite set $\{a^{n}bab^{n}\mid n\geq 0\}=\{ba,abab,aababb,aaababbb,\dotsc \}$ , where $a^{k}$ is a repeated k times (and n in particular represents the number of times production rule 1 has been applied).
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] This grammar is context-free (only single nonterminals appear as left-hand sides) and unambiguous.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] This grammar is not context-free due to rule 3 and it is ambiguous due to the multiple ways in which rule 2 can be used to generate sequences of S s.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] However, the language it generates is simply the set of all nonempty strings consisting of a s and/or b s.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] This is easy to see: to generate a b from an S , use rule 2 twice to generate $SSS$ , then rule 1 twice and rule 3 once to produce b .
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] This means we can generate arbitrary nonempty sequences of S s and then replace each of them with a or b as we please.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] That is, each production rule maps from one string of symbols to another, where the first string (the "head") contains an arbitrary number of symbols provided at least one of them is a nonterminal.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] A grammar is formally defined as the tuple $(N,\Sigma ,P,S)$ .
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Such a formal grammar is often called a rewriting system or a phrase structure grammar in the literature.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] This grammar defines the language $L(G)=\left\{a^{n}b^{n}c^{n}\mid n\geq 1\right\}$ where $a^{n}$ denotes a string of *n* consecutive a 's.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Thus, the language is the set of strings that consist of 1 or more a 's, followed by the same number of b 's, followed by the same number of c 's.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] When Noam Chomsky first formalized generative grammars in 1956, he classified them into types now known as the Chomsky hierarchy.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] The difference between these types is that they have increasingly strict production rules and can therefore express fewer formal languages.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Two important types are *context-free grammars* (Type 2) and *regular grammars* (Type 3).
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] The languages that can be described with such a grammar are called *context-free languages* and *regular languages*, respectively.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Although much less powerful than unrestricted grammars (Type 0), which can in fact express any language that can be accepted by a Turing machine, these two restricted types of grammars are most often used because parsers for them can be efficiently implemented.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] For example, all regular languages can be recognized by a finite-state machine, and for useful subsets of context-free grammars there are well-known algorithms to generate efficient LL parsers and LR parsers to recognize the corresponding languages those grammars generate.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] A *context-free grammar* is a grammar in which the left-hand side of each production rule consists of only a single nonterminal symbol.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] This restriction is non-trivial; not all languages can be generated by context-free grammars.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Those that can are called *context-free languages*.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] A context-free language can be recognized in $O(n^{3})$ time (*see* Big O notation) by an algorithm such as Earley's recogniser and in a sub-cubic time by fast matrix multiplication algorithms.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] That is, for every context-free language, a machine can be built that takes a string as input and determines in $O(n^{3})$ time whether the string is a member of the language, where n is the length of the string.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Deterministic context-free languages is a subset of context-free languages that can be recognized in linear time.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] There exist various algorithms that target either this set of languages or some subset of it.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] In regular grammars, the left hand side is again only a single nonterminal symbol, but now the right-hand side is also restricted.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] The right side may be the empty string, or a single terminal symbol, or a single terminal symbol followed by a nonterminal symbol, but nothing else.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] All languages generated by a regular grammar can be recognized in $O(n)$ time by a finite-state machine.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Although in practice, regular grammars are commonly expressed using regular expressions, some forms of regular expression used in practice do not strictly generate the regular languages and do not show linear recognitional performance due to those deviations.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Many extensions and variations on Chomsky's original hierarchy of formal grammars have been developed, both by linguists and by computer scientists, usually either in order to increase their expressive power or in order to make them easier to analyze or parse.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] A recursive grammar is a grammar that contains production rules that are recursive.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] For example, a grammar for a context-free language is left-recursive if there exists a non-terminal symbol *A* that can be put through the production rules to produce a string with *A* as the leftmost symbol.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] An example of recursive grammar is a clause within a sentence separated by two commas.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] All types of grammars in the Chomsky hierarchy can be recursive.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Though there is a tremendous body of literature on parsing algorithms, most of these algorithms assume that the language to be parsed is initially *described* by means of a *generative* formal grammar, and that the goal is to transform this generative grammar into a working parser.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] Strictly speaking, a generative grammar does not in any way correspond to the algorithm used to parse a language, and various algorithms have different restrictions on the form of production rules that are considered well-formed.
[src:antlr-parser/formal-grammar] An alternative approach is to formalize the language in terms of an analytic grammar in the first place, which more directly corresponds to the structure and semantics of a parser for the language.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] In computer science, an **LL parser** is a top-down parser for a restricted context-free language.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] It parses the input from **L**eft to right, performing **L**eftmost derivation of the sentence.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] An LL parser is called an LL(*k*) parser if it uses *k* tokens of lookahead when parsing a sentence.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] A grammar is called an LL(*k*) grammar if an LL(*k*) parser can be constructed from it.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] A formal language is called an LL(*k*) language if it has an LL(*k*) grammar.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The set of LL(*k*) languages is properly contained in that of LL(*k*+1) languages, for each *k* ≥ 0.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] A corollary of this is that not all context-free languages can be recognized by an LL(*k*) parser.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] An LL parser is called LL-regular (LLR) if it parses an LL-regular language.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The class of LLR grammars contains every LL(*k*) grammar for every *k*.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] For every LLR grammar there exists an LLR parser that parses the grammar in linear time.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Two nomenclative outlier parser types are LL(*) and LL(finite).
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] A parser is called LL(*)/LL(finite) if it uses the LL(*)/LL(finite) parsing strategy.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] LL(*) and LL(finite) parsers are functionally closer to PEG parsers.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] An LL(finite) parser can parse an arbitrary LL(*k*) grammar optimally in the amount of lookahead and lookahead comparisons.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The class of grammars parsable by the LL(*) strategy encompasses some context-sensitive languages due to the use of syntactic and semantic predicates and has not been identified.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] It has been suggested that LL(*) parsers are better thought of as TDPL parsers.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Against the popular misconception, LL(*) parsers are not LLR in general, and are guaranteed by construction to perform worse on average (super-linear against linear time) and far worse in the worst-case (exponential against linear time).
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] LL grammars, particularly LL(1) grammars, are of great practical interest, as parsers for these grammars are easy to construct, and many computer languages are designed to be LL(1) for this reason.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] LL parsers may be table-based, i.e. similar to LR parsers, but LL grammars can also be parsed by recursive descent parsers.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] According to Waite and Goos (1984), LL(*k*) grammars were introduced by Stearns and Lewis (1969).
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] For a given context-free grammar, the parser attempts to find the leftmost derivation.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Generally, there are multiple possibilities when selecting a rule to expand the leftmost non-terminal.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] To be efficient, the parser must be able to make this choice deterministically when possible, without backtracking.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] For some grammars, it can do this by peeking on the unread input (without reading).
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] In our example, if the parser knows that the next unread symbol is **(**, the only correct rule that can be used is 2.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Generally, an LL(*k*) parser can look ahead at *k* symbols.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] However, given a grammar, the problem of determining if there exists a LL(*k*) parser for some *k* that recognizes it is undecidable.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] For each *k*, there is a language that cannot be recognized by an LL(*k*) parser, but can be by an LL(*k* + 1) parser.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Let *G* be a context-free grammar and *k* ≥ 1.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] the following condition holds: the prefix of the string u of length k equals the prefix of the string v of length *k* implies $\beta =\gamma$ .
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] In this definition, S is the start symbol and A any non-terminal.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The already derived input w , and yet unread u and v are strings of terminals.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The Greek letters $\alpha$ , $\beta$ and $\gamma$ represent any string of both terminals and non-terminals (possibly empty).
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The prefix length corresponds to the lookahead buffer size, and the definition says that this buffer is enough to distinguish between any two derivations of different words.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The LL(*k*) parser is a deterministic pushdown automaton with the ability to peek on the next *k* input symbols without reading.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] This peek capability can be emulated by storing the lookahead buffer contents in the finite state space, since both buffer and input alphabet are finite in size.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] As a result, this does not make the automaton more powerful, but is a convenient abstraction.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The parser stack initially contains the starting symbol above the EOI: [ S **$** ].
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] If the last symbol to be removed from the stack is the EOI, the parsing is successful; the automaton accepts via an empty stack.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The states and the transition function are not explicitly given; they are specified (generated) using a more convenient *parse table* instead.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] If the parser cannot perform a valid transition, the input is rejected (empty cells).
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] To make the table more compact, only the non-terminal rows are commonly displayed, since the action is the same for terminals.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] An LL(1) parsing table for a grammar has a row for each of the non-terminals and a column for each terminal (including the special terminal, represented here as **$**, that is used to indicate the end of the input stream).
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Each cell of the table may point to at most one rule of the grammar (identified by its number).
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The algorithm to construct a parsing table is described in a later section, but first let's see how the parser uses the parsing table to process its input.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] In each step, the parser reads the next-available symbol from the input stream, and the top-most symbol from the stack.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] If the input symbol and the stack-top symbol match, the parser discards them both by moving to the next input symbol and popping the top-most symbol off the stack.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] This is repeated until the input symbol and top-most symbol on the stack do not match.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Thus, in its first step, the parser reads the input symbol '**(**' and the stack-top symbol 'S'.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The parsing table instruction comes from the column headed by the input symbol '**(**' and the row headed by the stack-top symbol 'S'; this cell contains '2', which instructs the parser to apply rule (2).
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The parser has to rewrite 'S' to '**(** S **+** F **)**' on the stack by removing 'S' from stack and pushing ')', 'F', '**+**', 'S', '**(**' onto the stack, and this writes the rule number 2 to the output.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] In the second step, the parser removes the '**(**' from its input stream and from its stack, since they now match.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Now the parser has an '**a'** on its input stream and an 'S' as its stack top.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The parsing table instructs it to apply rule (1) from the grammar and write the rule number 1 to the output stream.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The parser now has an '**a'** on its input stream and an 'F' as its stack top.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The parsing table instructs it to apply rule (3) from the grammar and write the rule number 3 to the output stream.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The parser now has an '**a'** on the input stream and an '**a**' at its stack top.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Because they are the same, it removes it from the input stream and pops it from the top of the stack.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The parser then has an '**+**' on the input stream and '**+**' is at the top of the stack meaning, like with 'a', it is popped from the stack and removed from the input stream.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] In the next three steps the parser will replace 'F' on the stack by '**a**', write the rule number 3 to the output stream and remove the '**a**' and '**)**' from both the stack and the input stream.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The parser thus ends with '**$**' on both its stack and its input stream.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] These steps are repeated until the parser stops, and then it will have either completely parsed the input and written a leftmost derivation to the output stream or it will have reported an error.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] In order to fill the parsing table, we have to establish what grammar rule the parser should choose if it sees a nonterminal *A* on the top of its stack and a symbol *a* on its input stream.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] It is easy to see that such a rule should be of the form *A* → *w* and that the language corresponding to *w* should have at least one string starting with *a*.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] For this purpose we define the *First-set* of *w*, written here as **Fi**(*w*), as the set of terminals that can be found at the start of some string in *w*, plus ε if the empty string also belongs to *w*.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] 4. do steps 2 and 3 until all **Fi** sets stay the same.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] where, for sets of words *U* and *V*, the truncated product is defined by $U\cdot V=\{(uv):1\mid u\in U,v\in V\}$ , and w:1 denotes the initial length-1 prefix of words w of length 2 or more, or *w*, itself, if w has length 0 or 1.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Unfortunately, the First-sets are not sufficient to compute the parsing table.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] This is because a right-hand side *w* of a rule might ultimately be rewritten to the empty string.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] So the parser should also use the rule *A* → *w* if *ε* is in **Fi**(*w*) and it sees on the input stream a symbol that could follow *A*.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Therefore, we also need the *Follow-set* of *A*, written as **Fo**(*A*) here, which is defined as the set of terminals *a* such that there is a string of symbols *αAaβ* that can be derived from the start symbol.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] We use **$** as a special terminal indicating end of input stream, and *S* as start symbol.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] 3. repeat step 2 until all **Fo** sets stay the same.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Now we can define exactly which rules will appear where in the parsing table.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] If the table contains at most one rule in every one of its cells, then the parser will always know which rule it has to use and can therefore parse strings without backtracking.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] It is in precisely this case that the grammar is called an *LL(1) grammar*.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] where an input is suffixed by *k* end-markers **$**, to fully account for the *k* lookahead context.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] This approach eliminates special cases for ε, and can be applied equally well in the LL(1) case.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Until the mid-1990s, it was widely believed that LL(*k*) parsing (for *k* > 1) was impractical, since the parser table would have exponential size in *k* in the worst case.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] This perception changed gradually after the release of the Purdue Compiler Construction Tool Set around 1992, when it was demonstrated that many programming languages can be parsed efficiently by an LL(*k*) parser without triggering the worst-case behavior of the parser.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Moreover, in certain cases LL parsing is feasible even with unlimited lookahead.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] By contrast, traditional parser generators like yacc use LALR(1) parser tables to construct a restricted LR parser with a fixed one-token lookahead.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] As described in the introduction, LL(1) parsers recognize languages that have LL(1) grammars, which are a special case of context-free grammars; LL(1) parsers cannot recognize all context-free languages.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The LL(1) languages are a proper subset of the LR(1) languages, which in turn are a proper subset of all context-free languages.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] In order for a context-free grammar to be an LL(1) grammar, certain conflicts must not arise.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] FIRST(*A*) is defined as the set of terminals that can appear in the first position of any string derived from *A*.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] FOLLOW(*B*) where *B* is any head of a rule of the form *B* → *wA*.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The FIRST sets of two different grammar rules for the same non-terminal intersect.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] FIRST(*E*) = {*b*, ε} and FIRST(*E* *a*) = {*b*, *a*}, so when the table is drawn, there is conflict under terminal *b* of production rule *S*.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Left recursion will cause a FIRST/FIRST conflict with all alternatives.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The FIRST and FOLLOW set of a grammar rule overlap.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] With an empty string (ε) in the FIRST set, it is unknown which alternative to select.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] The FIRST set of *A* is {*a*, ε}, and the FOLLOW set is {*a*}.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Can be applied when two alternatives start with the same symbol like a FIRST/FIRST conflict.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Substituting a rule into another rule to remove indirect or FIRST/FOLLOW conflicts.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Note that this may cause a FIRST/FIRST conflict.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] For a general method, see removing left recursion.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] This rule is nothing but list of Ts separated by '+'.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] In a regular expression form T ('+' T)*.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] Now there is no left recursion and no conflicts on either of the rules.
[src:antlr-parser/ll-parser] It can be shown that there does not exist any LL(k)-grammar accepting the language generated by this grammar.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The term has slightly different meanings in different branches of linguistics and computer science.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Traditional sentence parsing is often performed as a method of understanding the exact meaning of a sentence or word, sometimes with the aid of devices such as sentence diagrams.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] It usually emphasizes the importance of grammatical divisions such as subject and predicate.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Within computational linguistics the term is used to refer to the formal analysis by a computer of a sentence or other string of words into its constituents, resulting in a parse tree showing their syntactic relation to each other, which may also contain semantic information.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Some parsing algorithms generate a *parse forest* or list of parse trees from a string that is syntactically ambiguous.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The term is also used in psycholinguistics when describing language comprehension.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Within computer science, the term is used in the analysis of computer languages, referring to the syntactic analysis of the input code into its component parts in order to facilitate the writing of compilers and interpreters.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The term may also be used to describe a split or separation.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] In data analysis, the term is often used to refer to a process extracting desired information from data, e.g., creating a time series signal from a XML document.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The traditional grammatical exercise of parsing, sometimes known as *clause analysis*, involves breaking down a text into its component parts of speech with an explanation of the form, function, and syntactic relationship of each part.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] This is determined in large part from study of the language's conjugations and declensions, which can be quite intricate for heavily inflected languages.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] To parse a phrase such as "man bites dog" involves noting that the singular noun "man" is the subject of the sentence, the verb "bites" is the third person singular of the present tense of the verb "to bite", and the singular noun "dog" is the object of the sentence.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Techniques such as sentence diagrams are sometimes used to indicate relation between elements in the sentence.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Parsing was formerly central to the teaching of grammar throughout the English-speaking world, and widely regarded as basic to the use and understanding of written language.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] In some machine translation and natural language processing systems, written texts in human languages are parsed by computer programs.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Human sentences are not easily parsed by programs, as there is substantial ambiguity in the structure of human language, whose usage is to convey meaning (or semantics) amongst a potentially unlimited range of possibilities, but only some of which are germane to the particular case.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] So an utterance "Man bites dog" versus "Dog bites man" is definite on one detail but in another language might appear as "Man dog bites" with a reliance on the larger context to distinguish between those two possibilities, if indeed that difference was of concern.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] It is difficult to prepare formal rules to describe informal behaviour even though it is clear that some rules are being followed.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] In order to parse natural language data, researchers must first agree on the grammar to be used.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The choice of syntax is affected by both linguistic and computational concerns; for instance some parsing systems use lexical functional grammar, but in general, parsing for grammars of this type is known to be NP-complete.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Head-driven phrase structure grammar is another linguistic formalism which has been popular in the parsing community, but other research efforts have focused on less complex formalisms such as the one used in the Penn Treebank.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Shallow parsing aims to find only the boundaries of major constituents such as noun phrases.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Another popular strategy for avoiding linguistic controversy is dependency grammar parsing.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Most modern parsers are at least partly statistical; that is, they rely on a corpus of training data which has already been annotated (parsed by hand).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] This approach allows the system to gather information about the frequency with which various constructions occur in specific contexts.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] *(See machine learning.)* Approaches which have been used include straightforward PCFGs (probabilistic context-free grammars), maximum entropy, and neural nets.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Most of the more successful systems use *lexical* statistics (that is, they consider the identities of the words involved, as well as their part of speech).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] However such systems are vulnerable to overfitting and require some kind of smoothing to be effective.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Parsing algorithms for natural language cannot rely on the grammar having 'nice' properties as with manually designed grammars for programming languages.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] As mentioned earlier some grammar formalisms are very difficult to parse computationally; in general, even if the desired structure is not context-free, some kind of context-free approximation to the grammar is used to perform a first pass.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Algorithms which use context-free grammars often rely on some variant of the CYK algorithm, usually with some heuristic to prune away unlikely analyses to save time.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] *(See chart parsing.)* However some systems trade speed for accuracy using, e.g., linear-time versions of the shift-reduce algorithm.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] A somewhat recent development has been parse reranking in which the parser proposes some large number of analyses, and a more complex system selects the best option.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] In natural language understanding applications, semantic parsers convert the text into a representation of its meaning.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] In psycholinguistics, parsing involves not just the assignment of words to categories (formation of ontological insights), but the evaluation of the meaning of a sentence according to the rules of syntax drawn by inferences made from each word in the sentence (known as connotation).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] This normally occurs as words are being heard or read.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Neurolinguistics generally understands parsing to be a function of working memory, meaning that parsing is used to keep several parts of one sentence at play in the mind at one time, all readily accessible to be analyzed as needed.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Because the human working memory has limitations, so does the function of sentence parsing.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] This is evidenced by several different types of syntactically complex sentences that demonstrate potential issues for mental parsing of sentences.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The first, and perhaps most well-known, type of sentence that challenges parsing ability is the garden-path sentence.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] These sentences are designed so that the most common interpretation of the sentence appears grammatically faulty, but upon further inspection, these sentences are grammatically sound.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Garden-path sentences are difficult to parse because they contain a phrase or a word with more than one meaning, often their most typical meaning being a different part of speech.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] For example, in the sentence, "the horse raced past the barn fell", raced is initially interpreted as a past tense verb, but in this sentence, it functions as part of an adjective phrase.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Since parsing is used to identify parts of speech, these sentences challenge the parsing ability of the reader.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Another type of sentence that is difficult to parse is an attachment ambiguity, which includes a phrase that could potentially modify different parts of a sentence, and therefore presents a challenge in identifying syntactic relationship (i.e.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] A third type of sentence that challenges parsing ability is center embedding, in which phrases are placed in the center of other similarly formed phrases (i.e.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] "The rat the cat the man hit chased ran into the trap".) Sentences with 2 or in the most extreme cases 3 center embeddings are challenging for mental parsing, again because of ambiguity of syntactic relationship.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Within neurolinguistics there are multiple theories that aim to describe how parsing takes place in the brain.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The opposing, more contemporary model theorizes that within the mind, the processing of a sentence is not modular, or happening in strict sequence.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Rather, it poses that several different syntactic possibilities can be considered at the same time, because lexical access, syntactic processing, and determination of meaning occur in parallel in the brain.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] In this way these processes are integrated.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Although there is still much to learn about the neurology of parsing, studies have shown evidence that several areas of the brain might play a role in parsing.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] These include the left anterior temporal pole, the left inferior frontal gyrus, the left superior temporal gyrus, the left superior frontal gyrus, the right posterior cingulate cortex, and the left angular gyrus.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Although it has not been absolutely proven, it has been suggested that these different structures might favor either phrase-structure parsing or dependency-structure parsing, meaning different types of parsing could be processed in different ways which have yet to be understood.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Discourse analysis examines ways to analyze language use and semiotic events.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Persuasive language may be called rhetoric.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] A **parser** is a software component that takes input data (typically text) and builds a data structure – often some kind of parse tree, abstract syntax tree or other hierarchical structure, giving a structural representation of the input while checking for correct syntax.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The parsing may be preceded or followed by other steps, or these may be combined into a single step.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The parser is often preceded by a separate lexical analyser, which creates tokens from the sequence of input characters; alternatively, these can be combined in scannerless parsing.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Parsers may be programmed by hand or may be automatically or semi-automatically generated by a parser generator.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Parsing is complementary to templating, which produces formatted *output.* These may be applied to different domains, but often appear together, such as the scanf/printf pair, or the input (front end parsing) and output (back end code generation) stages of a compiler.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The input to a parser is typically text in some computer language, but may also be text in a natural language or less structured textual data, in which case generally only certain parts of the text are extracted, rather than a parse tree being constructed.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Parsers range from very simple functions such as scanf, to complex programs such as the frontend of a C++ compiler or the HTML parser of a web browser.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] An important class of simple parsing is done using regular expressions, in which a group of regular expressions defines a regular language and a regular expression engine automatically generating a parser for that language, allowing pattern matching and extraction of text.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] In other contexts regular expressions are instead used prior to parsing, as the lexing step whose output is then used by the parser.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] In the case of data languages, a parser is often found as the file reading facility of a program, such as reading in HTML or XML text; these examples are markup languages.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] In the case of programming languages, a parser is a component of a compiler or interpreter, which parses the source code of a computer programming language to create some form of internal representation; the parser is a key step in the compiler frontend.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Programming languages tend to be specified in terms of a deterministic context-free grammar because fast and efficient parsers can be written for them.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] For compilers, the parsing itself can be done in one pass or multiple passes – see one-pass compiler and multi-pass compiler.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The implied disadvantages of a one-pass compiler can largely be overcome by adding fix-ups, where provision is made for code relocation during the forward pass, and the fix-ups are applied backwards when the current program segment has been recognized as having been completed.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] An example where such a fix-up mechanism would be useful would be a forward GOTO statement, where the target of the GOTO is unknown until the program segment is completed.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] In this case, the application of the fix-up would be delayed until the target of the GOTO was recognized.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Conversely, a backward GOTO does not require a fix-up, as the location will already be known.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Context-free grammars are limited in the extent to which they can express all of the requirements of a language.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Informally, the reason is that the memory of such a language is limited.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The grammar cannot remember the presence of a construct over an arbitrarily long input; this is necessary for a language in which, for example, a name must be declared before it may be referenced.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] More powerful grammars that can express this constraint, however, cannot be parsed efficiently.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Thus, it is a common strategy to create a relaxed parser for a context-free grammar which accepts a superset of the desired language constructs (that is, it accepts some invalid constructs); later, the unwanted constructs can be filtered out at the semantic analysis (contextual analysis) step.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The following example demonstrates the common case of parsing a computer language with two levels of grammar: lexical and syntactic.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The first stage is the token generation, or lexical analysis, by which the input character stream is split into meaningful symbols defined by a grammar of regular expressions.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] For example, a calculator program would look at an input such as "`12 * (3 + 4)^2`" and split it into the tokens `12`, `*`, `(`, `3`, `+`, `4`, `)`, `^`, `2`, each of which is a meaningful symbol in the context of an arithmetic expression.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The lexer would contain rules to tell it that the characters `*`, `+`, `^`, `(` and `)` mark the start of a new token, so meaningless tokens like "`12*`" or "`(3`" will not be generated.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The next stage is parsing or syntactic analysis, which is checking that the tokens form an allowable expression.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] This is usually done with reference to a context-free grammar which recursively defines components that can make up an expression and the order in which they must appear.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] However, not all rules defining programming languages can be expressed by context-free grammars alone, for example type validity and proper declaration of identifiers.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] These rules can be formally expressed with attribute grammars.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The final phase is semantic parsing or analysis, which is working out the implications of the expression just validated and taking the appropriate action.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] In the case of a calculator or interpreter, the action is to evaluate the expression or program; a compiler, on the other hand, would generate some kind of code.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Attribute grammars can also be used to define these actions.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The *task* of the parser is essentially to determine if and how the input can be derived from the start symbol of the grammar.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] by expanding all alternative right-hand-sides of grammar rules.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] This is known as the primordial soup approach.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Very similar to sentence diagramming, primordial soup breaks down the constituencies of sentences.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] A parser can start with the input and attempt to rewrite it to the start symbol.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Intuitively, the parser attempts to locate the most basic elements, then the elements containing these, and so on.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] LL parsers and recursive-descent parser are examples of top-down parsers that cannot accommodate left recursive production rules.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Their algorithm is able to produce both left-most and right-most derivations of an input with regard to a given context-free grammar.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] An important distinction with regard to parsers is whether a parser generates a *leftmost derivation* or a *rightmost derivation* (see context-free grammar).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] LL parsers will generate a leftmost derivation and LR parsers will generate a rightmost derivation (although usually in reverse).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Some *graphical parsing* algorithms have been designed for visual programming languages.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Parsers for visual languages are sometimes based on graph grammars.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Adaptive parsing algorithms have been used to construct "self-extending" natural language user interfaces.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] A simple parser implementation reads the entire input file, performs an intermediate computation or translation, and then writes the entire output file, such as in-memory multi-pass compilers.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Lookahead establishes the maximum incoming tokens that a parser can use to decide which rule it should use.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Lookahead is especially relevant to LL, LR, and LALR parsers, where it is often explicitly indicated by affixing the lookahead to the algorithm name in parentheses, such as LALR(1).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Most programming languages, the primary target of parsers, are carefully defined in such a way that a parser with limited lookahead, typically one, can parse them, because parsers with limited lookahead are often more efficient.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] One important change to this trend came in 1990 when Terence Parr created ANTLR for his Ph.D. thesis, a parser generator for efficient LL(*k*) parsers, where *k* is any fixed value.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] LR parsers typically have only a few actions after seeing each token.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] They are shift (add this token to the stack for later reduction), reduce (pop tokens from the stack and form a syntactic construct), end, error (no known rule applies) or conflict (does not know whether to shift or reduce).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Most programming languages (except for a few such as APL and Smalltalk) and algebraic formulas give higher precedence to multiplication than addition, in which case the correct interpretation of the example above is 1 + (2 * 3).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Note that Rule4 above is a semantic rule.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] It is possible to rewrite the grammar to incorporate this into the syntax.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] However, not all such rules can be translated into syntax.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Reduces "1" to expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Shift "+" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule1).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Shift "2" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule3).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Reduce stack element "2" to Expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Reduce stack items [E, +, E] and new input "E" to "E" based on rule1.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Shift "*" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule2).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Shift "3" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule3).
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Reduce stack element "3" to expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Reduce stack items [E, *, E] and new input "E" to "E" based on rule2.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The parse tree and resulting code from it is not correct according to language semantics.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Reduce stack item 1 to simple Expression on input + based on rule3.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The lookahead is +, so we are on path to E +, so we can reduce the stack to E.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Shift + onto stack on input + in anticipation of rule1.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Shift 2 onto stack on input 2 in anticipation of rule3.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Reduce stack item 2 to Expression on input * based on rule3.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The lookahead * expects only E before it.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Now stack has E + E and still the input is *.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] It has two choices now, either to shift based on rule2 or reduction based on rule1.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Since * has higher precedence than + based on rule4, we shift * onto stack in anticipation of rule2.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Shift 3 onto stack on input 3 in anticipation of rule3.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Reduce stack item 3 to Expression after seeing end of input based on rule3.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Reduce stack items E * E to E based on rule2.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] Reduce stack items E + E to E based on rule1.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] The parse tree generated is correct and simply more efficient than non-lookahead parsers.
[src:antlr-parser/parsing] This is the strategy followed in LALR parsers.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] In computer science, a **recursive descent parser** is a kind of top-down parser built from a set of mutually recursive procedures (or a non-recursive equivalent) where each such procedure implements one of the nonterminals of the grammar.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Thus the structure of the resulting program closely mirrors that of the grammar it recognizes.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] A *predictive parser* is a recursive descent parser that does not require backtracking.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Predictive parsing is possible only for the class of LL(*k*) grammars, which are the context-free grammars for which there exists some positive integer *k* that allows a recursive descent parser to decide which production to use by examining only the next *k* tokens of input.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] The LL(*k*) grammars therefore exclude all ambiguous grammars, as well as all grammars that contain left recursion.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Any context-free grammar can be transformed into an equivalent grammar that has no left recursion, but removal of left recursion does not always yield an LL(*k*) grammar.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] A predictive parser runs in linear time.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Recursive descent with backtracking is a technique that determines which production to use by trying each production in turn.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Recursive descent with backtracking is not limited to LL(*k*) grammars, but is not guaranteed to terminate unless the grammar is LL(*k*).
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Even when they terminate, parsers that use recursive descent with backtracking may require exponential time.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Although predictive parsers are widely used, and are frequently chosen if writing a parser by hand, programmers often prefer to use a table-based parser produced by a parser generator, either for an LL(*k*) language or using an alternative parser, such as LALR or LR.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] This is particularly the case if a grammar is not in LL(*k*) form, as transforming the grammar to LL to make it suitable for predictive parsing is involved.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Predictive parsers can also be automatically generated, using tools like ANTLR.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Predictive parsers can be depicted using transition diagrams for each non-terminal symbol where the edges between the initial and the final states are labelled by the symbols (terminals and non-terminals) of the right side of the production rule.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Each nonterminal is defined by a rule in the grammar, except for *ident* and *number*, which are assumed to be implicitly defined.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] What follows is an implementation of a recursive descent parser for the above language in C.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] The parser reads in source code, and exits with an error message if the code fails to parse, exiting silently if the code parses correctly.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Notice how closely the predictive parser below mirrors the grammar above.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] There is a procedure for each nonterminal in the grammar.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] Parsing descends in a top-down manner until the final nonterminal has been processed.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] The program fragment depends the functions `peeksym`, which peeks at the current symbol; `consumesym`, which consumes the symbol to move to the next; and `error`, which displays an error message.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] These functions are assumed to be provided by the lexer.
[src:antlr-parser/recursive-descent-parser] The C++ front-end of the Clang compiler contains a hand-written parser based on the recursive-descent parsing algorithm.
[src:antlr-parser/www-antlr-org] is a tech lead at Google and until 2022 was a professor of data science / computer science at Univ. of San Francisco.
[src:antlr-parser/www-antlr-org] He is the maniac behind ANTLR and has been working on language tools since 1989.
